1.THE PURPOSE.

The primary purpose of this app is to provide users with detailed information about specific historical figures. Upon selecting a figure within the app, users can access their age and biography, offering valuable insights into the lives and notable contributions of these individuals.

This app is specifically designed for those who are interested in learning about impactful historical figures and prefer a more straightforward and accessible way to conduct their research. By catering to individuals who are keen on exploring the lives of historical figures and celebrities, the app serves as an essential resource for satisfying their curiosity and thirst for knowledge.

By providing a user-friendly platform to access this information, the app facilitates an engaging and informative experience for individuals looking to expand their knowledge of history and the people who shaped it. Overall, this app aims to bridge the gap between history enthusiasts and the captivating stories of historical figures, making historical research more accessible and enjoyable for everyone.

DESIGN CONSIDERATIONS

My design prioritizes accessibility and ease of navigation for users. With simple controls and straightforward click and delete options, users can effortlessly interact with the app. The app's name is displayed prominently at the top, accompanied by a carefully designed image. A dedicated space allows users to input the person's age, and clear (delete) and guarantee (click) buttons are conveniently located. Once the design is complete, a screenshot should be captured and placed under the 'design considerations' section. IMAGES

I specifically chose this picture to represent my historical figures because we are dealing with people who have passed away, and I didn't want the image to be too somber or dull. So, I selected a pink background with figures that have their eyes crossed out to represent their passing. Despite the somewhat playful nature of the image, it still conveys the idea of searching for deceased individuals and makes the process more fun and engaging.

CONTENT PRIORISATION

The necessary functionalities are displayed prominently, enabling users to effortlessly interact with the app's content. The information stored and presented within the app serves its intended purpose, ensuring a seamless and functional user experience

LEGIBLE TEXT CONTENT

A suitable font was carefully selected to ensure optimal legibility for users. The generously sized font is large enough to provide a comfortable reading experience. White text is consistently utilized across the app's buttons, offering clear visual cues for users to input their responses. The user interface is designed with minimal text, strategically placed to display only the most relevant information. This approach prioritizes clarity and ease of use, making interface elements clearly visible and user-friendly.

HAND POSITION CONTROLS

Presented in a visually striking manner, a pair of deep purple buttons are located in close proximity, their adjacency both eye-catching and purposeful. These buttons effectively serve as indicators for the fully functional, integral options of 'item selection' and 'item deletion,' allowing users to interact seamlessly with the interface.

# 4.GitHub and GitHub Actions

1\. Create a New GitHub Repository:

Go to the GitHub website (<https://github.com/>) and sign in to your account.

Click on the "+" icon in the top right corner and select "New repository".

Give your repository a name (ST10434932DoraMoroshadiLaneshaRatsoma), add a description (IMAD5112 Assignment 1) and choose public.

Click on the "Create repository" button.

2\. Initialize the Repository with a README File:

After creating the repository, you'll see an option to "Initialize this repository with a README". Check this option to create a README file.

Click on the "Create repository" button to finalize the creation of the repository.

3\. Commit and Push Your Project Files to the GitHub Repository:

In Android Studio, go to VCS (Version Control System) -> Import into Version Control -> Share Project on GitHub.

Log in to your GitHub account if prompted, and select the repository you created earlier.

Click on the "Share" button to push your project files to the GitHub repository.

4\. Regularly Commit and Push Your Code as You Make Progress:

After the initial push, continue making changes to your project in Android Studio.

Whenever you make significant progress or changes, commit your changes locally in Android Studio using VCS -> Commit Changes.

Once committed, push your changes to the GitHub repository using VCS -> Git -> Push.
